Not only in word2vec, but negative sampling is one of the cornerstones of the current trend in self-supervised learning and contrastive estimation and so on.

00:20.585 --> 00:26.812
So this, all of this, you know, it pops up in unlikely ways in other fields.

00:27.293 --> 00:37.485
And it sort of, I'm not going to say it originated here, but definitely it was introduced into the popular deep learning world right here.

00:38.266 --> 00:44.854
So they say an alternative to hierarchical softmax is noise contrastive estimation.

00:44.834 --> 00:54.020
So in noise contrastive estimation posits that a good model should be able to differentiate data from noise by means of logistic regression.

00:54.441 --> 00:55.885
That seems very reasonable.

00:56.667 --> 00:59.856
This is similar to the hinge loss and so on.

00:59.836 --> 01:17.633
While NCE can be shown to approximately maximize the log probability of the softmax, the skip-gram model is only concerned with learning high-quality vector representations, so we are free to simplify noise-constructive estimation as long as the vector representations retain their quality.

01:18.214 --> 01:21.220
We define negative sampling by this following objective.

01:21.200 --> 01:22.822
So this is very interesting.

01:22.842 --> 01:29.049
They see, okay, noise contrastive estimation, you know, it approximately maximizes the law.

01:29.089 --> 01:35.596
So the noise contrastive estimation would actually be the correct way to approximate their problem.

01:35.996 --> 01:43.865
However, they say, well, as long as, you know, as long as something reasonable comes out, we're free to change that up a bit.

01:43.885 --> 01:44.946
