01:54.217 --> 02:03.047
So it's written a bit differently from the original Softmax thing, because the original Softmax thing was written as a fraction, and here it's as a sum.

02:03.508 --> 02:11.457
But what you're trying to do in the negative sampling framework is you're trying to maximize the following.

02:11.437 --> 02:18.667
You're trying to maximize the inner product of the word you're considering and the words around them, okay?

02:18.687 --> 02:34.390
So you're trying to still predict the words around you, but now instead of having this prediction softmax over all of the classes, you only have the softmax over a subset of classes.

02:34.370 --> 02:50.708
So what you'll do is you sample words from your vocabulary at random and you sample K of them and you're simply trying to now minimize the inner product between those words and your word.

02:50.688 --> 02:54.014
Okay, so what does that ultimately lead to?

02:55.236 --> 02:57.420
It ultimately leads to the following.

02:58.302 --> 03:07.579
You have a word like this word here, negative, and what you're trying to do is you're not trying that much to predict the word sampling.

03:07.879 --> 03:12.848
What you're trying to do is you're trying to say that in my space right here,

03:12.828 --> 03:20.361
I simply want sampling to be closer than any other word that's not in the context window.

03:20.802 --> 03:25.710
Okay, so here is my word negative and here is my word sampling.

03:26.852 --> 03:29.116
And I want these two to be close.

03:29.577 --> 03:34.245
And if I sample another word, like here, this is the word cake.

03:34.225 --> 03:42.636
If I, sorry, if I sample that, I simply want that to be far away, farther than the word sampling.

03:43.418 --> 03:45.220
So this is now a comparative.

03:45.600 --> 03:48.805
It's not I classify sampling as the highest class.

03:49.185 --> 03:58.478
It's simply I want to classify the word sampling against the other classes higher.

03:59.588 --> 04:01.551
And this is now much, much easier.

04:01.631 --> 04:10.807
So instead of a thousand or 10,000 or a million way classification, I now maybe have, I have a K plus one way classification, right?

04:10.827 --> 04:11.909
Pretty easy, right?

04:11.929 --> 04:14.473
I simply sample K other words.

04:14.493 --> 04:23.588
And as I assume, because I have so many words, chances that I actually sample one that's in my context window is very small, right?

04:23.568 --> 04:27.374
So I simply sample other words and I say, well, these other words are random.

04:27.655 --> 04:31.441
They have nothing to do with the current frame that I'm looking at.

04:31.782 --> 04:42.960
So they should be, you know, they can be whatever they want, but at least they should be farther away than the words that are actually in my context.

04:44.932 --> 05:04.949
And that is negative sampling, the process of sampling negatives, this right here, and then making sure that the positives, which are these here, in this case, the words in the context are classified with a higher probability than the negatives for a given input word, right?

05:04.989 --> 05:06.872
This here is the input word.

05:10.177 --> 05:10.618
That's it.

05:10.858 --> 05:12.040
That's negative sampling.

05:12.180 --> 05:30.184
And of course, yeah, as I said, you recognize this from current things like self supervised learning, where you want to have the same image augmented twice, go through the pipeline, you know, you augment, you put a little bit of different noise, and then you have a different image.

05:30.965 --> 05:37.534
And at the end, you say, these two should be close together, while this other one should be far apart.

05:37.514 --> 05:45.753
It's the exact same thing here except that you have a different way of obtaining the positive and the negative samples.

05:46.254 --> 05:50.062
In this case, positive samples are everything that's in the context.

05:50.423 --> 05:54.392
Negative samples are just randomly sampled from the data set.

05:56.819 --> 06:00.685
And that, you know, works, of course, that works much, much, much faster.

